{"title_page": "Football in Kolkata", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:Salt Lake Stadium - Yuva Bharati Krirangan, Kolkata - Calcutta 5.jpg|thumb|270x270px|[[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan]] taking on [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] at the [[Salt Lake Stadium]].]]\n\n[[Association football|Football]] is one of the most popular sports in [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]].<ref name=\"Football Passion Kolkata\">{{cite web|title=Football - the passion play in Kolkata|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/football--the-passion-play-in-kolkata/211371-55.html|website=IBN Live|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>. [[East Bengal F.C.|East Bengal]] and [[Mohammedan S.C. (Kolkata)|Mohammedan]] are the heart of [[Kolkata]] football. Another professional club was formed on June 1st, 2020, by the merger of [[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan]] and [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]. Kolkata is known to be the hub of Indian football with the two most supported teams in the country being based within the city \u2013 Mohun Bagan and East Bengal. Both teams used to play against each other in the [[Kolkata derby]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mohun Bagan VS East Bengal|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/rivalries/newsid=1414458/index.html|website=FIFA|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> The city is also home to the biggest stadium in India, the [[Salt Lake Stadium|Vivekananda Yuba Bharati Krirangan]], which as of 2015 has a capacity of 85,000. The record attendance of 131,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/1064/i-league/2011/11/19/2762641/mohun-bagan-vs-east-bengal-the-deadly-derby-awaits-please-fasten-|title=The Deadly Derby Awaits - Please Fasten Your Seat Belts|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> came in a match between the said two teams in the [[East Bengal 4\u20131 Mohun Bagan|semifinal of the 1997 Federation Cup]].\n\n==Footballers who have visited Kolkata==\n\nBeing India's football capital, many international footballing personalities have graced Kolkata with their visit. In 1977 [[Mohun Bagan]] played a friendly match against the famous North American Soccer League club [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]] which featured [[Pel\u00e9]] . The match, which took place at Eden Gardens, had a match attendance of 80,000. The match ended 2-2. Others to visit Kolkata were Argentinean footballing legends [[Diego Maradona]] and current Argentinean footballing star [[Leo Messi]]. German legends like [[Franz Beckenbauer]] and [[Oliver Kahn]] have also made their visit. Best goalkeeper in football history, Russian footballer [[Lev Yashin]] made his first visit in 1955 and then in 1973. English World Cup winning legend [[Bobby Moore]] was the chief guest during the 1984 [[Nehru Cup]]. Emeka Ezuego, the Nigerian World Cupper played for [[East Bengal]] and [[Mohammedan S.C. (Kolkata)|Mohammedan Sporting]]. [[Majid Bishkar]] the Iranian World Cupper played for East Bengal and Mohammedan Sporting from 1980 - 1986. Cameroon footballing legend, [[Roger Milla]] came to play for Diamond Club in some exhibition matches in the Centenary Celebration of Mohun Bagan. Uruguay football captain [[Diego Forlan]] visited Kolkata in\n2010. [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]] visited in 2010. Julian Caminho visited Kolkata twice\u2014first in 1988 to play for East Bengal and again in 2011.\n[[MacDonald Mukansi]] played for East Bengal in 2007.\n\nOthers who also visited were [[Terry Paine]], [[Carlos Alberto Torres]], [[Enzo Francescoli]], Valencia Ramos, [[Jorge Burruchaga]], [[Ricardo Gareca]], [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kiss (footballer)|L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kiss]], [[Nicky Butt]], [[W\u0142odzimierz Smolarek]], [[Andrzej Buncol]], [[Eus\u00e9bio]], [[Ronald Koeman]], [[Paul Breitner]] and [[Swansea City]]'s [[Neil Taylor (footballer)|Neil Taylor]].\n\n==Footballers from West Bengal==\n\nThe state of West Bengal has contributed many legends to Indian football, such as\n\n*[[Chuni Goswami]], first [[Padma Shri]] awardee, awarded best striker of Asia in 1962.\n*[[Gostho Pal]] , footballer. Member of the Mohun Bagan team that won the IFA shield against a British team in the pre- independence period.\n*[[Krishanu Dey]] ,footballer, known as the \"Indian Maradona\".\n*[[Mohammed Salim (footballer)|Mohammed Salim]], first player from the Indian subcontinent to play overseas, in the year 1936 for the Scottish Club [[Celtic F.C.]].\n*[[Pradip Kumar Banerjee]], named Indian Footballer of the 20th Century by FIFA.\n*[[Shailen Manna]] , Footballer, the only Asian Footballer ever to be named among the 10 best Captains in the world by the English FA in 1953.\n*[[Subrata Paul]] , footballer playing for the Indian team, first Indian goalkeeper to play professionally for a foreign club in 1st division.\n*[[Sudip Chatterjee (footballer)|Sudip Chatterjee]] , footballer, considered among the finest in Indian football, declared AIFF player of the decade in 1994.\n\n==International Football==\n*[[Robin Dutt]], former manager of [[Bundesliga]] club, [[Werder Bremen]].\n*[[Neil Taylor (footballer)|Neil Taylor]], [[Wales|Welsh]] footballer of half-Bengali origin.\n\n==Arjuna award winners==\n\n* [[Pradip Kumar Banerjee|P.K Bannerjee]]\n* [[Chuni Goswami]]\n* Arun Lal Ghosh\n* [[Prasun Banerjee]]\n* Sudhir Karmakar\n* Shanti Mullick\n* [[Subrata Bhattacharya (footballer)|Subrata Bhattacharya]]\n* [[Deepak Mondal|Deepak Kumar Mondal]]\n* [[Subrata Pal]]\n\n==West Bengal football team==\n{{Main|West Bengal football team}}\n\nThe West Bengal football team is an Indian football team representing [[West Bengal]] in the [[Santosh Trophy]].\n\nThey have appeared in the Santosh Trophy finals 43 times, and have won the trophy 31 times, (the most by any team). Prior to 1972, the team competed as 'Bengal'.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Football in Greater Manchester]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Football in India}}\n{{Football in Kolkata}}\n\n[[Category:Football in Kolkata|       ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:Salt Lake Stadium - Yuva Bharati Krirangan, Kolkata - Calcutta 5.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan]] taking on [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] at the [[Salt Lake Stadium]].]]\n\n[[Association football|Football]] is one of the most popular sports in [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]].<ref name=\"Football Passion Kolkata\">{{cite web|title=Football - the passion play in Kolkata|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/football--the-passion-play-in-kolkata/211371-55.html|website=IBN Live|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>. [[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan]], [[East Bengal F.C.|East Bengal]] and [[Mohammedan S.C. (Kolkata)|Mohammedan]] is the heart of [[Kolkata]] football. Kolkata is known to be the hub of Indian football with the two most supported teams in the country being based within the city \u2013 Mohun Bagan and East Bengal. Both teams play against each other in the [[Kolkata derby]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mohun Bagan VS East Bengal|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/rivalries/newsid=1414458/index.html|website=FIFA|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> The city is also home to the biggest stadium in India, the [[Salt Lake Stadium|Vivekananda Yuba Bharati Krirangan]], which as of 2015 has a capacity of 85,000. The record attendance of 131,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/1064/i-league/2011/11/19/2762641/mohun-bagan-vs-east-bengal-the-deadly-derby-awaits-please-fasten-|title=The Deadly Derby Awaits - Please Fasten Your Seat Belts|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> came in a match between the said two teams in the [[East Bengal 4\u20131 Mohun Bagan|semifinal of the 1997 Federation Cup]].\n\n==Footballers who have visited Kolkata==\n\nBeing India's football capital, many international footballing personalities have graced Kolkata with their visit. In 1977 [[Mohun Bagan]] played a friendly match against the famous North American Soccer League club [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]] which featured [[Pel\u00e9]] . The match, which took place at Eden Gardens, had a match attendance of 80,000. The match ended 2-2. Others to visit Kolkata were Argentinean footballing legends [[Diego Maradona]] and current Argentinean footballing star [[Leo Messi]]. German legends like [[Franz Beckenbauer]] and [[Oliver Kahn]] have also made their visit. Best goalkeeper in football history, Russian footballer [[Lev Yashin]] made his first visit in 1955 and then in 1973. English World Cup winning legend [[Bobby Moore]] was the chief guest during the 1984 [[Nehru Cup]]. Emeka Ezuego, the Nigerian World Cupper played for [[East Bengal]] and [[Mohammedan S.C. (Kolkata)|Mohammedan Sporting]]. [[Majid Bishkar]] the Iranian World Cupper played for East Bengal and Mohammedan Sporting from 1980 - 1986. Cameroon footballing legend, [[Roger Milla]] came to play for Diamond Club in some exhibition matches in the Centenary Celebration of Mohun Bagan. Uruguay football captain [[Diego Forlan]] visited Kolkata in\n2010. [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]] visited in 2010. Julian Caminho visited Kolkata twice\u2014first in 1988 to play for East Bengal and again in 2011.\n[[MacDonald Mukansi]] played for East Bengal in 2007.\n\nOthers who also visited were [[Terry Paine]], [[Carlos Alberto Torres]], [[Enzo Francescoli]], Valencia Ramos, [[Jorge Burruchaga]], [[Ricardo Gareca]], [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kiss (footballer)|L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kiss]], [[Nicky Butt]], [[W\u0142odzimierz Smolarek]], [[Andrzej Buncol]], [[Eus\u00e9bio]], [[Ronald Koeman]], [[Paul Breitner]] and [[Swansea City]]'s [[Neil Taylor (footballer)|Neil Taylor]].\n\n==Footballers from West Bengal==\n\nThe state of West Bengal has contributed many legends to Indian football, such as\n\n*[[Chuni Goswami]], first [[Padma Shri]] awardee, awarded best striker of Asia in 1962.\n*[[Gostho Pal]] , footballer. Member of the Mohun Bagan team that won the IFA shield against a British team in the pre- independence period.\n*[[Krishanu Dey]] ,footballer, known as the \"Indian Maradona\".\n*[[Mohammed Salim (footballer)|Mohammed Salim]], first player from the Indian subcontinent to play overseas, in the year 1936 for the Scottish Club [[Celtic F.C.]].\n*[[Pradip Kumar Banerjee]], named Indian Footballer of the 20th Century by FIFA.\n*[[Shailen Manna]] , Footballer, the only Asian Footballer ever to be named among the 10 best Captains in the world by the English FA in 1953.\n*[[Subrata Paul]] , footballer playing for the Indian team, first Indian goalkeeper to play professionally for a foreign club in 1st division.\n*[[Sudip Chatterjee (footballer)|Sudip Chatterjee]] , footballer, considered among the finest in Indian football, declared AIFF player of the decade in 1994.\n\n==International Football==\n*[[Robin Dutt]], former manager of [[Bundesliga]] club, [[Werder Bremen]].\n*[[Neil Taylor (footballer)|Neil Taylor]], [[Wales|Welsh]] footballer of half-Bengali origin.\n\n==Arjuna award winners==\n\n* [[Pradip Kumar Banerjee|P.K Bannerjee]]\n* [[Chuni Goswami]]\n* Arun Lal Ghosh\n* [[Prasun Banerjee]]\n* Sudhir Karmakar\n* Shanti Mullick\n* [[Subrata Bhattacharya (footballer)|Subrata Bhattacharya]]\n* [[Deepak Mondal|Deepak Kumar Mondal]]\n* [[Subrata Pal]]\n\n==West Bengal football team==\n{{Main|West Bengal football team}}\n\nThe West Bengal football team is an Indian football team representing [[West Bengal]] in the [[Santosh Trophy]].\n\nThey have appeared in the Santosh Trophy finals 43 times, and have won the trophy 31 times, (the most by any team). Prior to 1972, the team competed as 'Bengal'.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Football in Greater Manchester]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Football in India}}\n{{Football in Kolkata}}\n\n[[Category:Football in Kolkata|       ]]\n", "name_user": "ArnabSaha", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Football_in_Kolkata"}
{"title_page": "Joan of France, Duchess of Brittany", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| realm=france\n| consort=yes\n| name            = Joan of Valois\n| full name       =\n| succession      = Duchess of Brittany\n| image           = Joan of France (1391\u20131433).jpg\n| caption         = \n| reign          =1 November 1399 \u2013 27 September 1433\n| spouse          = [[John V, Duke of Brittany]]\n| issue           =Anne<br />[[Isabella of Brittany|Isabelle, Countess of Laval]]<br />Margaret<br />[[Francis I, Duke of Brittany]]<br />Catherine<br />[[Peter II, Duke of Brittany]]<br />[[Gilles of Brittany|Gilles, Lord of Chantoc\u00e9]]\n| house           = [[House of Valois|Valois]]\n| father          = [[Charles VI of France]]\n| mother          = [[Isabeau of Bavaria]]\n| birth_date   = 24 January 1391\n| birth_place  =Ch\u00e2teau de Melun, [[Seine-et-Marne]], [[Kingdom of France]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1433|9|27|1391|1|24|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Vannes]], [[Morbihan]], [[Duchy of Brittany]]\n| burial_place = [[Vannes Cathedral]]\n| religion     = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n\n'''Joan of France''' ({{lang-fr|Jeanne}}; 24 January 1391 \u2013 27 September 1433) was Duchess of Brittany by marriage to [[John V, Duke of Brittany|John V]]. She was a daughter of [[Charles VI of France]] and [[Isabeau of Bavaria]].\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Mariage de Jean V de Bretagne et de Jeanne de France.png|thumb|left|The marriage of John and Joan by [[Froissart]].]]\n\nJoan married [[John V, Duke of Brittany]], in 1396. Three years after the wedding, her spouse became duke and she duchess of Brittany.\n\nAs duchess, Joan is perhaps most known for her role during the conflict between John V and the [[count of Penthi\u00e8vre|Counts of Penthi\u00e8vre]]. The Penthi\u00e8vre branch had lost the [[Breton War of Succession]] in the 1340s. As a result, they lost the ducal title of Brittany to the Montforts. The conclusion to the conflict took many years to confirm until 1365 when the [[Treaty of Gu\u00e9rande (1365)|Treaty of Gu\u00e9rande]] was signed. Despite the military loss and the diplomatic treaty, the Counts of Penthi\u00e8vre had not renounced their ducal claims to Brittany and continued to pursue them. In 1420, they invited John V to a festival held at Ch\u00e2tonceaux. He accepted the invitation, but when he arrived, he was captured and kept prisoner.\n\nThe Counts of Penthi\u00e8ve then spread rumours of his death, and moved him to a new prison each day. Joan of France called upon all the barons of Brittany to respond. They besieged all the castles of the Penthi\u00e8vre family one by one. Joan ended the conflict by seizing the dowager countess of Penthi\u00e8vre, [[Margaret of Clisson]], and forcing her to have the duke freed.\n\nJoan died in 1433, during her husband's reign.\n\nA [[Book of Hours]] by the [[Bedford Master]], ''[[Heures Lamoignon]]'', was dedicated to her.\n\n==Issue ==\nShe had seven children:\n\n*Anne (1409 \u2013 c. 1415)\n* [[Isabella of Brittany|Isabella]] (1411 \u2013 c. 1442), who in 1435 married [[Guy XIV of Laval]] and had 3 children with him.\n*Margaret (1412 \u2013 c. 1421)\n* [[Francis I, Duke of Brittany|Francis I]] (1414 \u2013 c. 1450), duke of Brittany\n*Catherine (1416 \u2013 c. 1421)\n* [[Peter II, Duke of Brittany|Peter II]] (1418 \u2013 c. 1457), duke of Brittany\n* [[Gilles of Brittany|Gilles]] (1420 \u2013 c. 1450), [[lord|seigneur]] of Chantoc\u00e9.\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Joan of France'''\n|2= 2. [[Charles VI of France]]\n|3= 3. [[Isabeau of Bavaria]]\n|4= 4. [[Charles V of France]]\n|5= 5. [[Joanna of Bourbon]]\n|6= 6. [[Stephen III, Duke of Bavaria]]\n|7= 7. [[Taddea Visconti]]\n|8= 8. [[John II of France]]\n|9= 9. [[Bonne of Bohemia]]\n|10= 10. [[Peter I, Duke of Bourbon]]\n|11= 11. [[Isabella of Valois (1313-1388)|Isabella of Valois]]\n|12= 12. [[Stephen II, Duke of Bavaria]]\n|13= 13. [[Elisabeth of Sicily, Duchess of Bavaria|Elizabeth of Sicily]]\n|14= 14. [[Bernab\u00f2 Visconti]]\n|15= 15. [[Beatrice Regina della Scala]]\n}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{commons category|Joan of France (1391\u20131433)}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*''The original version of this page was a translation of [[:fr:Jeanne de France (1391-1433)]]. From January 2013 the translation has been refined. ''\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Joan of Navarre, Queen of England|Joanna of Navarre]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Duchess consort of Brittany]]|years=1399\u20131433}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Isabella of Scotland]]}}\n{{End}}\n\n[[Category:1391 births]]\n[[Category:1433 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Valois]]\n[[Category:People of the Hundred Years' War]]\n[[Category:French princesses]]\n[[Category:Duchesses of Brittany]]\n[[Category:14th-century Breton people]]\n[[Category:14th-century French women]]\n[[Category:15th-century Breton people]]\n[[Category:15th-century French women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| realm=france\n| consort=yes\n| name            = Joan of Valois\n| full name       =\n| succession      = Duchess of Brittany\n| image           = Joan of France (1391\u20131433).jpg\n| caption         = \n| reign          =1 November 1399 \u2013 27 September 1433\n| spouse          = [[John V, Duke of Brittany]]\n| issue           =Anne<br />[[Isabella of Brittany|Isabelle, Countess of Laval]]<br />Margaret<br />[[Francis I, Duke of Brittany]]<br />Catherine<br />[[Peter II, Duke of Brittany]]<br />[[Gilles of Brittany|Gilles, Lord of Chantoc\u00e9]]\n| house           = [[House of Valois|Valois]]\n| father          = [[Charles VI of France]]\n| mother          = [[Isabeau of Bavaria]]\n| birth_date   = 24 January 1391\n| birth_place  =Ch\u00e2teau de Melun, [[Seine-et-Marne]], [[Kingdom of France]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1433|9|27|1391|1|24|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Vannes]], [[Morbihan]], [[Duchy of Brittany]]\n| burial_place = [[Vannes Cathedral]]\n| religion     = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n\n'''Joan of France''' ({{lang-fr|Jeanne}}; 24 January 1391 \u2013 27 September 1433) was Duchess of Brittany by marriage to [[John V, Duke of Brittany|John V]]. She was a daughter of [[Charles VI of France]] and [[Isabeau of Bavaria]].\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Mariage de Jean V de Bretagne et de Jeanne de France.png|thumb|left|The marriage of John and Joan by [[Froissart]].]]\n\nJoan married [[John V, Duke of Brittany]] in 1396. Three years after the wedding, her spouse became duke and she duchess of Brittany.\n\nAs duchess, Joan is perhaps most known for her role during the conflict between John V and the [[count of Penthi\u00e8vre|Counts of Penthi\u00e8vre]]. The Penthi\u00e8vre branch had lost the [[Breton War of Succession]] in the 1340s. As a result, they lost the ducal title of Brittany to the Montforts. The conclusion to the conflict took many years to confirm until 1365 when the [[Treaty of Gu\u00e9rande (1365)|Treaty of Gu\u00e9rande]] was signed. Despite the military loss and the diplomatic treaty, the Counts of Penthi\u00e8vre had not renounced their ducal claims to Brittany and continued to pursue them. In 1420, they invited John V to a festival held at Ch\u00e2tonceaux. He accepted the invitation, but when he arrived, he was captured and kept prisoner.\n\nThe Counts of Penthi\u00e8ve then spread rumours of his death, and moved him to a new prison each day. Joan of France called upon all the barons of Brittany to respond. They besieged all the castles of the Penthi\u00e8vre family one by one. Joan ended the conflict by seizing the dowager countess of Penthi\u00e8vre, [[Margaret of Clisson]], and forcing her to have the duke freed.\n\nJoan died in 1433, during her husband's reign.\n\nA [[Book of Hours]] by the [[Bedford Master]], ''[[Heures Lamoignon]]'', was dedicated to her.\n\n==Issue ==\nShe had seven children:\n\n*Anne (1409 \u2013 c. 1415)\n* [[Isabella of Brittany|Isabella]] (1411 \u2013 c. 1442), who in 1435 married [[Guy XIV of Laval]] and had 3 children with him.\n*Margaret (1412 \u2013 c. 1421)\n* [[Francis I, Duke of Brittany|Francis I]] (1414 \u2013 c. 1450), duke of Brittany\n*Catherine (1416 \u2013 c. 1421)\n* [[Peter II, Duke of Brittany|Peter II]] (1418 \u2013 c. 1457), duke of Brittany\n* [[Gilles of Brittany|Gilles]] (1420 \u2013 c. 1450), [[lord|seigneur]] of Chantoc\u00e9.\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Joan of France'''\n|2= 2. [[Charles VI of France]]\n|3= 3. [[Isabeau of Bavaria]]\n|4= 4. [[Charles V of France]]\n|5= 5. [[Joanna of Bourbon]]\n|6= 6. [[Stephen III, Duke of Bavaria]]\n|7= 7. [[Taddea Visconti]]\n|8= 8. [[John II of France]]\n|9= 9. [[Bonne of Bohemia]]\n|10= 10. [[Peter I, Duke of Bourbon]]\n|11= 11. [[Isabella of Valois (1313-1388)|Isabella of Valois]]\n|12= 12. [[Stephen II, Duke of Bavaria]]\n|13= 13. [[Elisabeth of Sicily, Duchess of Bavaria|Elizabeth of Sicily]]\n|14= 14. [[Bernab\u00f2 Visconti]]\n|15= 15. [[Beatrice Regina della Scala]]\n}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{commons category|Joan of France (1391\u20131433)}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*''The original version of this page was a translation of [[:fr:Jeanne de France (1391-1433)]]. From January 2013 the translation has been refined. ''\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Joan of Navarre, Queen of England|Joanna of Navarre]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Duchess consort of Brittany]]|years=1399\u20131433}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Isabella of Scotland]]}}\n{{End}}\n\n[[Category:1391 births]]\n[[Category:1433 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Valois]]\n[[Category:People of the Hundred Years' War]]\n