and their populations: Somalia 2005 (draft)|url=https://docs.unocha.org/sites/dms/Somalia/UNDP-POP-RURAL-URBAN%202005.pdf|publisher=UNDP|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/SO/04/Qansaxdheere2.html Qansaxdheere, Somalia Page]\n\n{{coord missing|Somalia}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Bay, Somalia]]\n\n\n{{somalia-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Malaakh", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qansahdhere"}
{"title_page": "Sharpe's Company (TV programme)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Sharpe's Company\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Title screen from ''Sharpe's Company''\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Bernard Cornwell]] (novel)<br />[[Charles Wood (playwright)|Charles Wood]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = Tom Clegg\n| starring             = [[Sean Bean]]<br />[[Daragh O'Malley]]<br />[[Hugh Fraser (actor)|Hugh Fraser]]<br />[[Michael Byrne (actor)|Michael Byrne]]<br />[[Pete Postlethwaite]]<br />[[Assumpta Serna]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Dominic Muldowney<br />[[John Tams]]\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Malcolm Craddock]]<br />[[Muir Sutherland]] (exec.)\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 102 minutes<ref>{{cite web |title= SHARPE - SHARPE'S COMPANY |url= https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/sharpe-sharpes-company-1994 |website= British Board of Film Classification |accessdate= 2 April 2020 }}</ref>\n| company              = \n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = \n| first_aired          = 25 May 1994\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = [[Sharpe's Eagle (TV programme)|Sharpe's Eagle]]\n| followed_by          = [[Sharpe's Enemy (TV programme)|Sharpe's Enemy]]\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Sharpe's Company''''' is a British [[television drama]], the third of [[Sharpe (TV series)|a series]] that follows the career of [[Richard Sharpe (fictional character)|Richard Sharpe]], a British soldier during the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. This episode is based on the [[Sharpe's Company (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Bernard Cornwell]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nIt is 1812. General [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Wellesley]] ([[Hugh Fraser (actor)|Hugh Fraser]]) is ready to invade Spain from Portugal. But two formidable fortresses stand in the way. When the first, [[Ciudad Rodrigo]], is taken, [[William Lawford|Colonel Lawford]] is severely wounded and forced to relinquish command of the [[South Essex Regiment]], depriving Captain Sharpe ([[Sean Bean]]) of an influential friend.\n\nColonel Windham ([[Clive Francis]]), the new commander, brings his own officers, so Sharpe is demoted to lieutenant and is humiliated by being put in charge of the baggage and losing command of his \"chosen men\" to an aristocratic officer ([[Marc Warren]]) who [[sale of commissions|purchased the commission]] of the South Essex's Light Company. Worse, one of the reinforcements is Sergeant [[Obidiah Hakeswill]] ([[Pete Postlethwaite]]), an old enemy from Sharpe's days in India.\n\nMeanwhile, Sharpe's lover, Teresa ([[Assumpta Serna]]), tells him that he has a baby daughter living with her family in [[Badajoz]], the second fortress town. Not knowing who she is, Hakeswill tries to rape her, but proves no match for her. Teresa then slips into Badajoz to spy on the French and to see her baby.\n\nTo cause trouble for Sharpe, Hakeswill steals from the officers and plants a picture frame belonging to Windham in the kit of Sharpe's right-hand man, Sergeant Harper ([[Daragh O'Malley]]). When it is found, the colonel has Harper flogged. Later, during a night skirmish, a turncoat French soldier escapes the besieged town, bearing a dispatch and a letter from Teresa, but he is shot and killed. Sharpe recovers the letter, which contains a map showing where she is staying, but on his way back Hakeswill tries to shoot Sharpe in the confusion, but kills a young ensign ([[William Mannering]]) who has the misfortune to step in front of him at that exact moment.\n\nEventually the walls of [[Battle of Badajoz (1812)|Badajoz are breached]], but the first assault falters. Sharpe rallies the men and leads them into the town. Hakeswill gets to Teresa first due to the letter he stole from Sharpe, [[List of Sharpe series characters#In the TV series|Harry Price]], one of Sharpe's officers, intervenes and is shot and apparently killed by Hakeswill while trying to protect Teresa. (Price reappears, in ''[[Sharpe's Waterloo]]'', this time played by Nicholas Irons.) Sharpe is not far behind and stops Hakeswill, who is wounded in the process, but Hakeswill still manages to get away.\n\nFor his bravery and because many of the other officers have been killed, Sharpe gets back command of his Light Company. Harper is exonerated when he finds the missing portrait of Windham's wife hidden in Hakeswill's [[shako]] and returns it to the colonel.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sean Bean]] as [[Richard Sharpe (fictional character)|Richard Sharpe]]\n* [[Daragh O'Malley]] as Sergeant [[Patrick Harper (fiction)|Patrick Harper]]\n* [[Assumpta Serna]] as [[Teresa Moreno|Comandante Teresa Moreno]]\n* [[Clive Francis]] as Colonel Windham \n* [[Nicholas Jones (actor)|Nicholas Jones]] as Colonel Fletcher \n* [[Michael Byrne (actor)|Michael Byrne]] as [[Nairn (fictional character)|Major Nairn]]\n* [[Hugh Fraser (actor)|Hugh Fraser]] as [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Lord Wellington]]\n* [[Michael Cochrane]] as [[Sir Henry Simmerson]]\n* [[Pete Postlethwaite]] as Sergeant [[Obadiah Hakeswill]]\n* [[Michael Mears]] as Rifleman Francis Cooper\n* [[John Tams]] as [[Daniel Hagman|Rifleman Daniel Hagman]]\n* [[Jason Salkey]] as [[Sergeant Harris|Rifleman Harris]]\n* [[Lyndon Davies]] as Rifleman Ben Perkins\n* [[William Mannering]] as  Ensign Matthews ([[Viscount]])\n* [[Scott Cleverdon]] as [[Harry Price (fictional character)|Lieutenant Harry Price]]\n* [[Robert Morgan (British actor)|Robert Morgan]] as Major Collett\n* [[Peter Gunn (actor)|Peter Gunn]] as Private Clayton\n* [[Louise Germaine]] as Sally Clayton\n* [[Soo Drouet]] as Mrs. Grimes\n* [[Marc Warren]] as Captain Rymer\n* [[Peter Birrel]] as Don Moreno\n* [[Tat Whalley]] as Hope\n* [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Pradon]] as Reynier\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0111156|title=Sharpe's Company}}\n* [http://www.sharpefilm.com/company/index.html Sharpe's Company at SharpeFilm.com]\n\n{{Bernard Cornwell}}\n\n[[Category:1994 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:1990s historical films]]\n[[Category:1990s war films]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on historical novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on military novels]]\n[[Category:Napoleonic Wars films]]\n[[Category:Sharpe (TV series)|Company]]\n[[Category:War television films]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1812]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Sharpe's Company\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Title screen from ''Sharpe's Company''\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Bernard Cornwell]] (novel)<br />[[Charles Wood (playwright)|Charles Wood]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = Tom Clegg\n| starring             = [[Sean Bean]]<br />[[Daragh O'Malley]]<br />[[Hugh Fraser (actor)|Hugh Fraser]]<br />[[Michael Byrne (actor)|Michael Byrne]]<br />[[Pete Postlethwaite]]<br />[[Assumpta Serna]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Dominic Muldowney<br />[[John Tams]]\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Malcolm Craddock]]<br />[[Muir Sutherland]] (exec.)\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 102 minutes<ref>{{cite web |title= SHARPE - SHARPE'S COMPANY |url= https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/sharpe-sharpes-company-1994 |website= British Board of Film Classification |accessdate= 2 April 2020 }}</ref>\n| company              = \n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = \n| first_aired          = 25 May 1994\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = [[Sharpe's Eagle (TV programme)|Sharpe's Eagle]]\n| followed_by          = [[Sharpe's Enemy (TV programme)|Sharpe's Enemy]]\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Sharpe's Company''''' is a British [[television drama]], the third of [[Sharpe (TV series)|a series]] that follows the career of [[Richard Sharpe (fictional character)|Richard Sharpe]], a British soldier during the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. This episode is based on the [[Sharpe's Company (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Bernard Cornwell]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nIt is 1812. General [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Wellesley]] ([[Hugh Fraser (actor)|Hugh Fraser]]) is ready to invade Spain from Portugal. But two formidable fortresses stand in the way. When the first, [[Ciudad Rodrigo]], is taken, [[William Lawford|Colonel Lawford]] is severely wounded and forced to relinquish command of the [[South Essex Regiment]], depriving Captain Sharpe ([[Sean Bean]]) of an influential friend.\n\nColonel Windham ([[Clive Francis]]), the new commander, brings his own officers, so Sharpe is demoted to lieutenant and is humiliated by being put in charge of the baggage and losing command of his \"chosen men\" to an aristocratic officer ([[Marc Warren]]) who [[sale of commissions|purchased the commission]] of the South Essex's Light Company. Worse, one of the reinforcements is Sergeant [[Obidiah Hakeswill]] ([[Pete Postlethwaite]]), an old enemy from Sharpe's days in India.\n\nMeanwhile, Sharpe's lover, Teresa ([[Assumpta Serna]]), tells him that he has a baby daughter living with her family in [[Badajoz]], the second fortress town. Not knowing who she is, Hakeswill tries to rape her, but proves no match for her. Teresa then slips into Badajoz to spy on the French and to see her baby.\n\nTo cause trouble for Sharpe, Hakeswill steals from the officers and plants a picture frame belonging to Windham in the kit of Sharpe's right-hand man, Sergeant Harper ([[Daragh O'Malley]]). When it is found, the colonel has Harper flogged. Later, during a night skirmish, a turncoat French soldier escapes the besieged town, bearing a dispatch and a letter from Teresa, but he is shot and killed. Sharpe recovers the letter, which contains a map showing where she is staying, but on his way back Hakeswill tries to shoot Sharpe in the confusion, but kills a young ensign ([[William Mannering]]) who has the misfortune to step in front of him at that exact moment.\n\nEventually the walls of [[Battle of Badajoz (1812)|Badajoz are breached]], but the first assault falters. Sharpe rallies the men and leads them into the town. Hakeswill gets to Teresa first due to the letter he stole from Sharpe, [[List of Sharpe series characters#In the TV series|Harry Price]], one of Sharpe's officers, intervenes and is shot and apparently killed by Hakeswill while trying to protect Teresa. (Price reappears, in ''[[Sharpe's Waterloo]]'', this time played by Nicholas Irons.) Sharpe is not far behind and stops Hakeswill, who is wounded in the process, but Hakeswill still manages to get away.\n\nFor his bravery and because many of the other officers have been killed, Sharpe gets back command of his Light Company. Harper is exonerated when he finds the missing portrait of Windham's wife hidden in Hakeswill's [[shako]] and returns it to the colonel.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sean Bean]] as [[Richard Sharpe (fictional character)|Richard Sharpe]]\n* [[Daragh O'Malley]] as Sergeant [[Patrick Harper (fiction)|Patrick Harper]]\n* [[Assumpta Serna]] as [[Teresa Moreno|Comandante Teresa Moreno]]\n* [[Clive Francis]] as Colonel Windham \n* [[Nicholas Jones (actor)|Nicholas Jones]] as Colonel Fletcher \n* [[Michael Byrne (actor)|Michael Byrne]] as [[Nairn (fictional character)|Major Nairn]]\n* [[Hugh Fraser (actor)|Hugh Fraser]] as [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Lord Wellington]]\n* [[Michael Cochrane]] as [[Sir Henry Simmerson]]\n* [[Pete Postlethwaite]] as Sergeant [[Obadiah Hakeswill]]\n* [[Michael Mears]] as Rifleman Francis Cooper\n* [[John Tams]] as [[Daniel Hagman|Rifleman Daniel Hagman]]\n* [[Jason Salkey]] as [[Sergeant Harris|Rifleman Harris]]\n* [[Lyndon Davies]] as Rifleman Ben Perkins\n* [[William Mannering]] as  Ensign Matthews ([[Viscount]])\n* [[Scott Cleverdon]] as [[Harry Price (fictional character)|Lieutenant Harry Price]]\n* [[Robert Morgan (British actor)|Robert Morgan]] as Major Collett\n* [[Peter Gunn (actor)|Peter Gunn]] as Private Clayton\n* [[Louise Germaine]] as Sally Clayton\n* [[Soo Drouet]] as Mrs. Grimes\n* [[Marc Warren]] as Captain Rymer\n* [[Peter Birrel]] as Don Moreno\n* [[Tat Whalley]] as Hope\n* [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Pradon]] as Reynier\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0111156|title=Sharpe's Company}}\n* [http://www.sharpefilm.com/company/index.html Sharpe's Company at SharpeFilm.com]\n\n{{Bernard Cornwell}}\n\n[[Category:1994 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:1990s historical films]]\n[[Category:1990s war films]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on historical novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on military novels]]\n[[Category:Napoleonic Wars films]]\n[[Category:Sharpe (TV series)|Company]]\n[[Category:War television films]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1812]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharpe%27s_Company_(TV_programme)"}
